  <feedback condition="$correct">$correctFeedback</feedback>
  
  <feedback condition="$usedH"><p>It looks like you computed the location of the minimum, rather than the min itself.</p>
  </feedback>
  <feedback condition="$ans9.numSubmissions > 2 and $ans9.creditAchieved != 1"> 
    <p>The minimum of a <ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/algebra/chapter/topic-5-6-optimization-using-parabolas/">quadratic function</ref> is equal to the value of the function at the vertex, when the parabola opens upwards (or, equivalently, when <m>a > 0</m>). We can determine the vertex from the given quadratic function <me>f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c</me> several different ways:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><p>Use the formula for the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex given by <me>x = -\frac{b}{2a}.</me> For more information, see the textbook link labeled "Optimization using Parabolas" below.</p></li>
    <li><p><ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/algebra/chapter/topic-5-7-completing-the-square/">Complete the square</ref> to obtain an equation in vertex form, i.e. transform the given equation into one that resembles <me>y = a(x - h)^2 + k.</me></p></li>
  </ul>
  </feedback>

 


